22w.title: Introductory Bayesian problems
22w.clickbait: Bayesian problems to try to solve yourself, before beginning to learn about Bayes
22w.text:
[todo: Each of the introductory problems has been broken out into its own page (diseasitis, sparking_widgets, blue_oysters, sockdresser_search, IIRC). All pages that depend on this as a requisite should be made to depend on the individual problems instead, and then this page should be deleted.]

The below examples will be used throughout the Arbital guide to Bayes' rule. You're encouraged to try solving them on your own now, and you're also encouraged to _not_ look at the answers yet (but we've included links to the sections where the answers are found, just in case).

## Testing for Diseasitis

You are screening a set of patients for a disease, which we'll call Diseasitis. Based on prior studies, you expect that around 20% of the patients in the screening population will in fact have Diseasitis. You are testing for the presence of the disease using a color-changing tongue depressor with a sensitive chemical strip. Among patients with Diseasitis, 90% turn the tongue depressor black. However, 30% of the patients without Diseasitis will also turn the tongue depressor black. Among all the patients with black tongue depressors, what percentage have Diseasitis?

Answer in: [1x1]

## Socks in dresser drawers

You left your socks somewhere in your room. You think there's a 4/5 chance that they're somewhere in your dresser, so you start looking through your dresser's 8 drawers. After checking 6 drawers at random, you haven't found your socks yet. What is the probability you will find your socks in the next drawer you check?

Answer in: [1y6]

## Widget mental arithmetic

10% of widgets are bad and 90% are good. 4% of good widgets emit sparks, and 12% of bad widgets emit sparks. If a widget is sparking, how would you **mentally** calculate the chance that it's a bad widget, making the operations as simple as possible so that you don't lose track of your mental arithmetic?

Answer in:  [1x7]

## Blue pearl eggs

Two barrels each contain plastic eggs painted various colors. In both barrels, 11% of the eggs contain valuable pearls and 89% are empty. In the first barrel, 4% of the pearl-containing eggs are painted blue, and 8% of the non-pearl-containing eggs are painted blue. In the second barrel, 13% of the pearl-containing eggs are painted blue, and 26% of the non-pearl-containing eggs are painted blue. Would you rather have a blue egg from the first or second barrel?  (There's a way to see the solution at a glance.)

Answer in:  [1zh]
